544":"1544","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","of Wiesa, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Saxony, Germany","Wiesa Chemnitz Sachsen Deutschland":"Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Saxony, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MEISSNER","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Gerhard, Erwin, Hans, Claus, Fritz, Heinz, Siegfried, Ewald, Hanns, Helmuth.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Meissen in Germany, earlier (968  AD ) recorded as <i>Misna</i>, <i>Misina</i>, named for the small river Misna (today Meisabach), whose name is very ancient, probably pre-Slavic. The place was famous in the Middle Ages for the fine linen cloth produced there, and the German surname may also be an occupational name for a manufacturer or seller of such wares."],"variants":[{"name":"Miesner","meanings":["German: variant of   Meissner  . Compare   Misner  ."]},{"name":"Mizener","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Meissner  ."]},{"name":"Mizner","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Meissner   or   Miesner  . Compare   Misner  .","Slovak (also <b>Mízner</b>): from German   Miesner  ."]},{"name":"Maixner","meanings":["German: variant of   Meissner  ."]},{"name":"Meixner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Gerhard, Helmut, Joerg, Kurt.","German: variant of <b>Meichsner</b>, which is a variant of   Meissner  . This form is also found in Czechia."]},{"name":"Misener","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Meissner  . Compare   Misner  ."]},{"name":"Meisner","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Meissner  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicolaus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Nicolaus MEISSNER was born in 1520, in Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Saxony, Germany. He married Rosina GLASER in 1544, in Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Saxony, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1520–":"1520–Surnud","1522–Female":"1522–Surnud","1545–1613":"1545–1613","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1613":"1613","1545":"1545","1544":"1544","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","of Wiesa, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Saksamaa","Wiesa Chemnitz Sachsen Deutschland":"Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1520–":"1520–Kuollut","1522–Female":"1522–Kuollut","1545–1613":"1545–1613","1520–Male":"1520–Kuollut","1613":"1613","1545":"1545","1544":"1544","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","of Wiesa, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Saksa","Wiesa Chemnitz Sachsen Deutschland":"Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Saksa"},"fr":{"1520–":"1520–Décédé","1522–Female":"1522–Décédée","1545–1613":"1545–1613","1520–Male":"1520–Décédé","1613":"1613","1545":"1545","1544":"1544","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","of Wiesa, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Allemagne","Wiesa Chemnitz Sachsen Deutschland":"Wiesa, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Allemagne","lifeSummary":"Nic